Let's break BTC ETF approval down ‚Üì

üî∏ What are Bitcoin ETFs?

Imagine a bucket where instead of buying Bitcoin directly, you buy a piece of this bucket that tracks its price.

This is called an exchange-traded fund, or ETF for short.

You're basically betting on Bitcoin's price without actually holding any Bitcoin yourself.

üî∏ So, what's the deal?

When you go for a Bitcoin ETF, you're not directly buying the crypto.

Instead, you're buying a share of this fund through your regular brokerage account.

The fund's job is to manage the money, buying and selling#Bitcoinon your behalf.

Now, getting one of these ETFs up and running isn't a walk in the park.

The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), a big financial watchdog, needs to give the green light.

They take their time, checking everything thoroughly, which makes the approval process quite lengthy and complicated.

üî∏ Why should the crypto community care about a Bitcoin ETF?

Well, if the SEC says yes, it's expected to open the floodgates for billions of dollars to pour into the market.

More money means more demand, which can push Bitcoin's price up.

Analysts are keeping their eyes peeled, some even saying that Bitcoin's price could skyrocket to between $100,000 and $200,000.

Here's why Bitcoin could return to all-time highs before the 2024 halving!‚¨áÔ∏è

The Bitcoin halving happens every 4 years. It cuts the new supply of coins in half. The next one is in April 2024.

History shows that the$BTCprice tends to rise a year before and after each halving. This is because lower supply usually leads to higher demand.

Research shows Bitcoin price rallies 32% on average in the 2 months right before each halving.

Bitcoin's last all-time high was around $69,000 in Nov 2021. 

A 32% rally from today's $52,000 price would put Bitcoin back around its former peak.

So the theory is: Based on historical data, Bitcoin could hit a new all-time high again before the 2024 halving.

Of course, past performance doesn't guarantee future results. 

But the crypto community expects history to repeat itself with the next halving.

If demand rises as supply gets cut, Bitcoin could be on track to break $69,000 again before April 2024.
